english:
  title: A Second Memorial
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your humble servant Geun, with utmost reverence and trepidation, bows low to present this memorial to Your Majesty.

    Your servant has pondered the affairs of the realm and observed that while circumstances may appear alike, their consequences differ greatly. In times of peace and stability, one must uphold the proper way; in times of peril and urgency, one must employ expedient measures. Should one follow expedience during peaceful times, the proper moment is lost and calamity follows—this cannot be overlooked.

    Those who hold dominion over the realm must pass their authority through hereditary succession—this is the proper way of ritual. When vassal lords inherit their domains, they must receive the Mandate from the Son of Heaven—this too is the proper way. In ancient times, when a lord's son completed his mourning period, he would dress in a scholar's robes and present himself to the Son of Heaven. Only after receiving carriages and vestments from the Son of Heaven could he inherit his father's rank and return to govern his state.

    When the Zhou dynasty declined and the various states grew strong and overreaching, the Marquis of Zhao, bemused by palace favorites, passed his throne to a young illegitimate son and called himself "Lord Father." Later, seeking to divide his kingdom among other sons, he brought calamity upon himself, ultimately perishing of starvation while his state collapsed into chaos—a laughingstock for ten thousand ages.

    From the Tang dynasty's Tianbao era through the Song's end, abdications occurred, driven either by crisis or imperial illness. Yet all were emergency measures; never has one heard of such actions taken without cause. When frontier lords appointed successors without first seeking the Son of Heaven's permission, informing him afterward, this began in the Tang's decline when military governors grew unruly. Yet such usurpers were soon destroyed—none endured.

    Only in the previous dynasty did Loyal Announcer King transfer to Loyal Respectful King, and Loyal Respectful King to Loyal Wise King—both during times of peace. Yet Loyal Announcer King, nephew of the Great Ancestor Emperor, received his title as Grand Commandant from Yuan and enjoyed the Emperor's favor. Content to dwell in Yandu, he had no wish to return. Thus he personally petitioned the Emperor, transferring his realm to Loyal Respectful King. The latter, wishing to maintain family precedent, also petitioned and transferred to Loyal Wise King. Both first sought permission before transferring—adhering to proper ritual. Yet Loyal Announcer King, having long remained in Yanking, eventually suffered slander and was sent to Tibet. Loyal Respectful King fell into discord with Loyal Wise King, and father and son sued each other—shaming posterity. Though they observed the form of requesting first, the benefit never came, only harm followed. This cannot be called commendable; let it be a mirror.

    When the Spurious Court reached Kings Oji and Chang, they dared to enthrone first and petition afterward—abandoning proper precedent. Yet King Oji's arrogance and depravity reached heaven, and his invasion of Liaodong provided opportunity. Our Supreme King raised the banner of righteousness, turned his forces to support the Central State, and his loyalty became manifest. The Emperor praised this and overlooked the irregularity. Yet at that time, your servant and others, including Evaluator-of-Proposals Yun Seung-soon, received King Chang's commission to journey to the capital. There, Minister of Rites Li Yuan-ming rebuked us: "You received your rank from the king and serve as prime minister. Without informing the king, you privately gave your rank to another, and that person, without royal sanction, privately accepted it from you. Would not the king punish you? Your realm's ruler receives the Emperor's mandate to inherit the royal rank. Now, without seeking permission, you privately grant it to his son. What manner of ritual is this?" The catastrophe pressed upon us so urgently we could not respond. Yet the Emperor's reply contained words about establishing one of different surname as king and that tributary ministers possessed no wisdom. By this, King Chang and his heir lost their realm. Had our Supreme King not raised righteousness and turned his forces, the suffering of our people would have been unspeakable.

    When our Supreme King transferred to the Former King, his illness grew grave, and Jeong Do-jeon dared defy the Emperor's command and sought to invade Liaodong, placing a young bastard on the throne—the crisis was acute. The Central State itself faced the High Emperor's passing and the Jianwen Emperor's accession, with affairs in disorder, so it overlooked the matter. When the Former King transferred to Your Majesty, the Central State chanced to face the Yan rebellion and had no time for external conflict. Yet in its response, doubts were repeatedly expressed. All these were fortunate escapes—not flawless strategy.

    Now the Central State enjoys perfect peace, and our realm faces no urgent crisis. Yet Your Majesty seeks to follow the old path, transferring to the Crown Prince before petitioning the Emperor. This is precisely what your servant means by "same circumstances, different consequences."

    In former times, both sides faced danger, so we could employ expedience, and they permitted it likewise. Now circumstances differ. We face no crisis, so we must observe proper form and petition first. They face no emergency, so they too will judge by proper precedent. Should they censure us by standard practice, with what shall we respond? How can this not be a case of identical circumstances yet different consequences, requiring careful examination?

    Your Majesty may think: "If we petition first, the Emperor might refuse, saying the Crown Prince is too young. If we transfer first and then report, having already done so, surely the Emperor must approve." Yet imperial approval rests upon whether the matter is proper, not upon whether transfer has occurred.

    Your Majesty has shown your servants extraordinary favor. We are deeply grateful and ask nothing more. Should we suddenly resign, seeking personal ease, Your Majesty would wonder: "I granted them unusual honor, yet they hastily withdraw from me. What is in their hearts?" Such doubts would naturally arise. When the Son of Heaven grants refined music to lords, this is a rare distinction indeed. Now that the Emperor has granted Your Majesty such favor, you should personally conduct ceremonies in the ancestral temple, demonstrating your profound gratitude for the Emperor to hear. Instead, you hastily decline this imperial gift. What will the Emperor think?

    Your servant hears that envoy Huang Yan recently tells people: "Your Majesty's sincerity in serving the great power remains as before, but the chief ministers execute their duties carelessly." Should the Emperor hear this, and then receive word of a change in rule, he will believe Huang Yan's words all the more. He will think powerful ministers monopolize state power, deposing and enthrone at will, scheming to use a young ruler against the Central State—as Choe Yeong once did. Though he may not immediately dispatch punitive forces, he will surely summon the chief ministers to question them. Can they refuse the Emperor's summons as Jeong Do-jeon did? If not, resentment will be seeded. If they must go, Your Majesty will in one day, without cause, cast your loyal and devoted ministers into an unfathomable abyss beyond salvation. There, subjected to severe interrogation, crimes will be fabricated against them. Their end will not be mere execution—it will become grounds for the Emperor to justify launching punitive forces against our realm.

    Your Majesty relies solely upon your sincere loyalty and the Emperor's favor, giving it no thought. Yet you wish to abdicate to one small and weak, and the entire realm weeps in anguish. Your servant humbly begs Your Majesty to think deeply and act with care.

    Your Majesty may dismiss your servant's words as impossibly remote from reality. Yet initially, you surely believed that granting the succession to the proper Crown Prince would be legitimate and proper, and all the realm would joyfully follow. Now, instead, rumors spread without cease. If Your Majesty cannot foresee the people's discontent, how can you be certain the great power above will overlook it?

    The *Book of Changes* says: "In all undertakings, deliberate at the beginning. Without deliberation at the start, troubles will surely come at the end." If this applies even to small matters, how much more to great affairs? Though the Crown Prince is of the proper line, he is yet young and weak, the people's hearts have not gathered to him—this shows heaven's will has not yet assembled. If Your Majesty ignores the realm's precarious state and defies both heaven and the people, forcing succession upon the young and weak, you abandon the ancestral temple and state altars to ruin.

    Your servant humbly begs Your Majesty to think deeply and act with care. Reclaim the imperial seal and personally hear the ten thousand matters. When the Crown Prince has grown in years, when virtue shines forth, when the people gladly follow, when heaven's mandate has gathered—then first report to the court and await their clear approval before transferring. Thus the ancestral altars will be most fortunate, and the realm most fortunate.
  footnotes:
    - The 'proper way' (정도/正道) refers to established ritual and precedent, while the 'expedient way' (권도/權道) involves necessary departures from protocol during crises—a fundamental distinction in classical Chinese political philosophy.
    - Gwon Geun references historical examples of problematic succession transfers, including the disastrous reign of Zhao Wuling of the Warring States period and various Tang dynasty precedents, to argue that abdication without proper imperial approval leads to calamity.
    - This memorial concerns the abdication of King Taejong in favor of the young Crown Prince (later King Sejong). Gwon Geun warns that transferring power before obtaining imperial Chinese sanction risks international complications and the persecution of loyal ministers.
    - Choe Yeong was a late Goryeo general notorious for manipulating royal succession to seize power—an example Gwon Geun uses to warn against allowing ministers to control succession without proper procedures.
    - The mention of Huang Yan (黃儼), a powerful eunuch at the Ming court, reflects the real diplomatic tensions of the era and concerns that irregular successions might be perceived as evidence of ministerial overreach.
